===Etymology===
From {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|atome|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|atomus||smallest particle|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ἄτομος||indivisible|tr=atomos|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}, from {{term|ἀ-||not|tr=a-|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}} + {{term|τέμνω||I cut|tr=temnō|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈætəm/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"{t@m/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The smallest, [[indivisible]] constituent part or unit of something.
# {{context|physics|lang=en}} The smallest possible amount of matter which still retains its identity as a chemical element, now known to consist of a [[nucleus]] surrounded by [[electrons]].
# {{context|mathematics|lang=en}} A non-zero member of a {{w|Boolean algebra}} that is not a [[union]] of any other elements.
# {{context|historical|lang=en}} A theoretical particle of matter, imagined to be incapable of further division; the smallest possible unit of substance.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} The smallest medieval unit of time, equal to fifteen ninety-fourths of a [[second]].
# {{context|computing|programming|[[Lisp]]|lang=en}} An individual [[number]] or [[symbol]], as opposed to a [[list]]. A [[scalar]] value.
# A very [[small]] amount; a [[whit]].
#* Sir J. Ross
#*: There was not an '''atom''' of water.
#* '''1873''', {{w|Isabella Macdonald Alden}} (as "Pansy"), ''Three People'', Western Tract and Book Society (1873), [http://books.google.com/books?id=XMUsAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA325 page 325]:
#*: "I have hardly the faintest '''atom''' of hope," answered this honest, earnest man.
#* {{RQ:Orwell Animal Farm|1}}
#*: {{...}} those of us who are capable of it are forced to work to the last '''atom''' of our strength

